% ===== Page 4 =====
\section*{6.4 Application of estimators to real data\ldots}

\begin{itemize}
\item \ldots produces $\hat{\gamma}$, which is akin to $\hat{k}, \hat{d}, \hat{c}$.

\item This $\hat{\gamma}$ can be used \emph{only} for non-rigorous, intuitive considerations for many reasons, including:
\begin{itemize}
\item applied to any $\mathbf{k}$, $(X,Y)$ spits out some $\hat{\gamma}$,
\item we never know if a real world $\mathbf{k}$ satisfies all the assumptions under which the consistency of $(X,Y)$ is proven,
\item if $\mathbf{k}$ does not satisfy these assumptions, we do not know whether $(X,Y)$ is still consistent,
\item even if $(X,Y)$ is still consistent, the speed of convergence is not known, so that we do not even know how close $\hat{\gamma}$ is \emph{expected} to be to $\gamma$ for any given $n$,
\item examples of adversarial $\mathbf{k}$'s that deceive $(X,Y)$ for any finite $n$ are easy to construct, e.g., independent samples from:

\begin{center}
\begin{minipage}{0.4\textwidth}
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
\draw[->] (0,0) -- (3.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
\draw[->] (0,0) -- (0,3) node[above] {$P(x)$};
\draw[thick, cyan] (0.3,2) -- (2,2) -- (2.2,1.8) -- (2.5,0.3);
\draw[dashed] (2,0) -- (2,2);
\node at (2,-0.3) {$\epsilon n?$};
\node[cyan] at (1.5,2.7) {Power law};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}{0.4\textwidth}
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
\draw[->] (0,0) -- (3.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
\draw[->] (0,0) -- (0,3) node[above] {$P(x)$};
\draw[thick, cyan] (0.3,2.5) .. controls (1,2) and (1.5,1.5) .. (2.5,1.2) -- (2.7,1.2) -- (2.7,0.3);
\draw[dashed] (2.7,0) -- (2.7,1.2);
\node at (2.7,-0.3) {$\epsilon n?$};
\node[cyan] at (1.8,2.7) {Not Power law};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{minipage}
\end{center}

\textit{[Description of figures: Two side-by-side plots showing probability distributions $P(x)$ versus $x$. The left plot is labeled ``Power law'' and shows a flat plateau followed by a sharp power-law decay starting around $x = \epsilon n?$. The right plot is labeled ``Not Power law'' and shows a smooth curved decay (not following a power law) that transitions to a flat tail around $x = \epsilon n?$. Both illustrate adversarial distributions that can deceive power-law estimators for finite sample sizes.]}

\end{itemize}

\item Yet, the $(X,Y)$'s in the previous sections are the best things we currently have, in the sense that they are at least known to work well in the controlled settings of the lab environment, so if someone forces you to estimate the $\gamma$ in any real data, the best you can do is to use them.

\end{itemize}

