% ===== Page 8 =====
\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\textit{[Figure 3 consists of three heatmap-style tables labeled (a), (b), and (c), showing the breakdown of degree sequences for different network types.]}

\textbf{(a) Undirected networks:} A horizontal bar chart divided into four segments labeled NPL, HPL, PL (unlabeled middle segment), and PL (rightmost green segment). The segments contain the numbers 7, 11, 7, and 10 respectively, representing the distribution of undirected networks across classification categories.

\textbf{(b) In-degrees and Out-degrees:} A two-dimensional heatmap table with Out-degrees on the vertical axis (labeled NPL, HPL, PL from top to bottom with values 5, 5; 9, 2, 2; 27, 2, 3; 7, 0, 0; 6, 1, 0) and In-degrees on the horizontal axis (labeled NPL HPL and PL at top with values 20, 19). The table is a $5 \times 3$ grid showing the joint distribution of in-degree and out-degree classifications. Numbers in cells represent counts of networks: top row shows 20 and 19; second row shows 3 and 2; third row shows 10 and 12; fourth row shows 5 and 2; fifth row shows 2 and 3. Color shading ranges from dark purple (0.50) to white (0.00) representing the fraction of networks, with a color bar on the right showing the scale from 0.00 to 0.50. Marginal totals appear on the left and top edges.

\textbf{(c) Domain 1 and Domain 2:} A two-dimensional heatmap table showing the joint classification for bipartite networks. The vertical axis is labeled ``Domain 2'' with categories NPL (value 2), NPL (value 6), HPL (value 11), PL (value 6), and PL (value 8). The horizontal axis is labeled ``Domain 1'' with categories NPL, HPL, and PL, with marginal values 9, 7, and 13. The $5 \times 3$ grid contains counts: first row shows 2, 0, 2; second row shows 4, 2, 5; third row shows 1, 3, 2; fourth row shows 2, 2, 4. Color shading follows the same scale as panel (b), from 0.00 to 0.50, with a color bar on the right.

\caption{The breakdown of the degree sequences of the considered real-world networks into the three classes defined in Sec.~V: not power-law (NPL), hardly power-law (HPL), and power-law (PL), the latter containing the divergent second moment (DSM) subclass, shown in green. The full data appear in Tables I--III. The data are shown for (a) undirected, (b) directed, and (c) bipartite networks. The numbers in the boxes are the numbers of networks falling within the corresponding (sub)class. In directed networks, the in- and out-degree sequences are classified separately. Similarly, in bipartite networks, the degree sequences of nodes of types 1 and 2 (domains 1 and 2) are classified separately as well. The numbers of networks with all possible combinations of the two classifications are then shown in the squares, along with the marginals outside of the squares. The color shading in the squares shows the fraction of directed and bipartite networks in each category.}
\label{fig:3}
\end{figure}

